  <static seed="2631" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/PolynomialMultiplication/PolynomialMultiplicationApplication10.pg">
    <statement><p>A rectangle<rsq/>s length is <m>4</m> feet shorter than <m>3 \text{ times}</m> its width. If we use <m>w</m> to represent the rectangle<rsq/>s width, use a polynomial to represent the rectangle<rsq/>s area in expanded form.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ \text{area}=}</m><fillin characters="18" name="AnSwEr0001"/> square feet</p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>3w^{2}-4w</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>The rectangle<rsq/>s width is <m>w</m> feet. Since the rectangle<rsq/>s length is <m>4</m> feet shorter than <m>3 \text{ times}</m> its width, its length is <m>3w-4</m> feet. A rectangle<rsq/>s area formula is:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ \text{area}=(\text{length})\cdot(\text{width}) }</m></p>
<p>After substitution, we have:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \text{area} \amp = (\text{length})\cdot(\text{width}) \\
                     \amp = (3w-4)w \\
                     \amp ={3w^{2}-4w}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The rectangle<rsq/>s area is <m>{3w^{2}-4w}</m> square feet.</p>
</solution>
